<subSubSection id="C2ED8D401B0818C8793BF808DFA3A50C" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="DA51BCA9FBE3E8138A6C90935F529B8D" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E5D56A9438FCCF8294730212617F5373" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">
Collected with flowers and fruits in July and November. In the area, there is only one rainy period with the highest levels of precipitation between the months of May to July and with less precipitation between December to February (
<bibRefCitation id="FACFF6FAFCF1CDA35EB9770E326CB5BD" author="Jaramillo, RA" journalOrPublisher="Cenicafe" pageId="9" pageNumber="96" pagination="102 - 113" publicationUrl="https://www.cenicafe.org/es/publications/arc051%2802%29102-113.pdf" refId="B11" refString="Jaramillo, RA, Chaves, CB, 2000. Distribucion de la precipitacion en Colombia analizada mediante conglomeracion estadistica. Cenicafe 51 (2): 102 - 113, https://www.cenicafe.org/es/publications/arc051%2802%29102-113.pdf" title="Distribucion de la precipitacion en Colombia analizada mediante conglomeracion estadistica." url="https://www.cenicafe.org/es/publications/arc051%2802%29102-113.pdf" volume="51" year="2000">Jaramillo and Chaves 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Flowering coincides with less rainy periods.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7ECE6076142707822D9634C9785FC926" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="39FCAAEC908C707A9042517D818FC92F" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Habitat and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="07D67EA71CEA3DAFC390BD94201F4B5B" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">
<taxonomicName id="633A04E40CCF7A45868744CEC1336798" authorityName="HumbertoMend. &amp; R. Romero" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Microlicia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Microlicia colombiana" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="colombiana">
<emphasis id="B65F5B7866378FDACB5864C74D432D96" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">Microlicia colombiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to northeastern Andes of Colombia towards the Orinoquian flank. This species is only known from the type locality in the department of 
<normalizedToken id="CA44FED2F94BB9976F7333A0EFD61B4A" originalValue="Boyacá">Boyaca</normalizedToken>
near the southern border of Pisba National Natural Park, and a nearby second locality in the department of Casanare, between 2000 to 2400 m elevation (Figure 
<figureCitation id="8CDB5241C0BF587CFDB075BBEB914629" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Distribution of Microlicia. A Distribution of M. colombiana and the most similar species in northern South America (Red dots: M. colombiana; Yellow point: M. guanayana; Green triangles: M. benthamiana) B Distribution of Microlicia in South America and wind currents (Red point depicts distribution of M. colombiana, white dots are other species of the genus)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.122.34171.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/304999" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">4A</figureCitation>
). It grows in open areas of 
<normalizedToken id="72003726621D3B65E07CD99018B786C7" originalValue="sub-páramo">sub-paramo</normalizedToken>
vegetation on white sandy soil covered with sphagnum (Figure 
<figureCitation id="994EDF2801869EAC621474EEF05866B7" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Microlicia colombiana HumbertoMend. &amp; R. Romero. A Habit B Flowering branch C Sub-paramo habitat at te type locality D, E Sandy soils and substrate of the type lovality (all photos by David Granados)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.122.34171.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/304998" pageId="5" pageNumber="92">3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
